        <h3 style="color: #1a1a1a; font-family: 'SF Compact Display', -apple-system, BlinkMacSystemFont, 'Segoe UI', Roboto, Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif, 'Apple Color Emoji', 'Segoe UI Emoji', 'Segoe UI Symbol'; font-size: 1.375em; font-weight: 700; line-height: 1.16em; margin: 1em 0 0.625em 0;">
         <strong>
          Radical Compensation
         </strong>
        </h3>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         The history of financial innovation is the history of democratizing access to upside. As more stakeholders share in the wealth they create, they\xe2\x80\x99re incentivized to collaborate, experiment, and innovate. There would be no Silicon Valley, for example, without the Employee Stock Ownership Plan (ESOP).
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         When a group of engineers known as The Traitorous Eight left Shockley Semiconductor Laboratory to found Fairchild Semiconductor in 1957, investors rewarded their treachery with a new type of compensation: stock options. If Fairchild did well, they would do very well.
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         Options seemed radical then; they\xe2\x80\x99re commonplace now. Startups are risky, and they don\xe2\x80\x99t have nearly as much money as their more established competitors. Options, which give employees a small chance at a life-changing payout, are how startups compensate for that risk, and they\xe2\x80\x99ve been the pixie dust that has fueled Silicon Valley\xe2\x80\x99s meteoric half-century rise.
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         When the products startups made were things like microchips and database software, it made sense that the employees should share in that upside. But what happens when the boundaries between employment and work begin to blur? When
         <em>
          people
         </em>
         become the product.
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         In just the past week, both
         <a href="https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFUMGugyAQ_JpyNCyK4oFDL_0Ng7BVUgUDS41__2h7eMkms7uzm8mMNYRLTJc-YiZWMqbJOw29UK3sRuZ050BJxXyenglxN37TlAqyo8ybt4Z8DN8PzoVkqx4G_kQQ4Lgw88y5Qjva0TmwIHo1CPbRmUxxHoNFjW9MVwzINr0SHfnW3m_iUes8zyajbZb4rtM92dW_MdcW3WJSRWfIVAApx0Hw2nHOAcYWhBRcjJ3i8LlS0PfKZWhW2pnXlapXMEIrWz400Ji8DSiKOMLr1vF9EU0ucyZjX42NO0s6RJpj8mGp9Gs1O25fotqfKu4leLomDGbe0P2SoV-WX6N0HagDnnlDIky_5ScuNfS97CSrai7WVMO_0B_sJYQ_" style="color: #1a1a1a; text-decoration: underline;">
          Airbnb
         </a>
         and
         <a href="https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFUEuuwyAMPE1ZRmBCCAsW3fQaER83QU0gAtIot3-0XTzJ0tgeW6MZZyrOKV96T6WSo2CegtdsgJGLXhGve89GMZJQpmdG3ExYdc0Hkv2wa3CmhhS_H5SCIIu2nCsxSOWV6ZmQzoIZPPTmiZZR6wT56Ezm8AGjQ41vzFeKSFa91LqXG7_f4NHqPM-uoOvm9G7TPbslvLG0Fv1sckNvqmnApAI5qtZRShlTnIEACgr4yD5XUgBQ6QvrlrqRoBvXzphiXHAqO9aZskqEA_b4uvV0m6Erhy3VuFfn0kayjqnalEOcG_1azIbrl2j-p4bbEUO9JozGruh_0dRfmF-n9dpRRzzLirVi_i0_eY1yGEQvSFPzqcUa_4X-AJg4hLE" style="color: #1a1a1a; text-decoration: underline;">
          DoorDash
         </a>
         filed their S-1\xe2\x80\x99s ahead of going public. Many employees and investors will become multi-millionaires. Some will officially become billionaires. Uber and Lyft have added more than $30 billion to their combined market caps over the past month, enriching investors and employees alike.\xc2\xa0 That\xe2\x80\x99s a beautiful thing. The American dream.
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         But millions more who fall in a new gray area between \xe2\x80\x9cemployee\xe2\x80\x9d and \xe2\x80\x9cproduct\xe2\x80\x9d -- the Dashers who deliver your food, the drivers behind the wheel of your Uber and Lyft, the influencers who create content on Instagram, and the Hosts who let you into their home -- don\xe2\x80\x99t participate in that upside.
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         The result is that the economic interests of the largest internet platforms are poorly aligned with their most valuable contributors, their users.
        </p>
        <h3 style="color: #1a1a1a; font-family: 'SF Compact Display', -apple-system, BlinkMacSystemFont, 'Segoe UI', Roboto, Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif, 'Apple Color Emoji', 'Segoe UI Emoji', 'Segoe UI Symbol'; font-size: 1.375em; font-weight: 700; line-height: 1.16em; margin: 1em 0 0.625em 0;">
         <strong>
          User-Generated Everything
         </strong>
        </h3>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         The digital economy has radically changed the nature of the relationship between customers and corporations. Individuals have switched from being passive consumers to being an essential force in creating value, either through their actual work (Airbnb, DoorDash, Uber, Sofar artists, Wikipedia editors, Airbnb hosts) or their data (Facebook, Google, etc). Today, the user is not only the consumer. The user does the work.
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         In the gig economy, users who contribute time and data are rewarded linearly \xe2\x80\x94 to earn more, an Uber driver needs to drive more. The platform grows exponentially, while the platform\xe2\x80\x99s most important asset \xe2\x80\x94 the driver \xe2\x80\x94 earns linearly.
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         As large platforms get richer off their users\xe2\x80\x99 personal data and time, people are trying to regain control. We spent the last fifteen years working for gig money, likes, retweets, or follows. The platforms gave us reputation or cash, but no
         <strong>
          ownership, upside, or voice in its evolution.
         </strong>
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         But the balance of power is shifting, and companies are recognizing the need to better align with their users.
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         Over the past few years, we\xe2\x80\x99ve been seeing a lot of experiments in this space.
        </p>
        <ul style="margin: 1em 0;">
         <li style="margin: 3.75px 0 3.75px 7.5px; mso-special-format: bullet;">
          <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0;">
           Andrew Yang\xe2\x80\x99s
           <strong>
            <a href="https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFkM2O6yAMRp-m7IgCIX8LFrO5rxE5wWlRCSAwN8rbD2kXIyF9whYc-2xA-Azp0jFkYiVjWqzRYpBT16uZGa2MmPqJ2bzsCfEA6zSlgiyW1dkNyAb_edG2smcvPbc4zAqGcROi30aUYh7ltKtJ7cooA-zmLFCMRb-hxv-YruCROf0iivnR_Tzkv3rO82xOm9A0WzjqPVMdsmaI1lckB28SnvwC_8w8OvCcAo9w8SsUvod0Z-IGCLgJmD1xMIaXWL9gVstWtkKIWXR9146NaCC7OmuR0b8fqj2essllzQTb--azpH2gNSTrn7X9fsGB7tOoFpaaR_GWrgU9rA7NVxB9lX72pSui9nhmh0SYvsXb2jQOQ696VmkmVLn-D_QLHweNtw" style="color: #1a1a1a; text-decoration: underline;">
             Data Dividend
            </a>
           </strong>
           would force platforms to pay users for their data.
          </p>
         </li>
         <li style="margin: 3.75px 0 3.75px 7.5px; mso-special-format: bullet;">
          <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0;">
           California\xe2\x80\x99s AB5 would have forced Uber and Lyft to treat drivers like employees instead of contractors until voters supported Prop 22, which exempts gig economy companies\xe2\x80\xa6 for now.
          </p>
         </li>
        </ul>
        <ul style="margin: 1em 0;">
         <li style="margin: 3.75px 0 3.75px 7.5px; mso-special-format: bullet;">
          <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0;">
           Denim startup
           <a href="https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFkM2O6yAMRp-m7IgCIX8LFrO5rxE5wWlRCSAwN8rbD2kXIyF9whYc-2xA-Azp0jFkYiVjWqzRYpBT16uZGa2MmPqJ2bzsCfEA6zSlgiyW1dkNyAb_edG2smcvPbc4zAqGcROi30aUYh7ltKtJ7cooA-zmLFCMRb-hxv-YruCROf0iivnR_Tzkv3rO82xOm9A0WzjqPVMdsmaI1lckB28SnvwC_8w8OvCcAo9w8SsUvod0Z-IGCLgJmD1xMIaXWL9gVstWtkKIWXR9146NaCC7OmuR0b8fqj2essllzQTb--azpH2gNSTrn7X9fsGB7tOoFpaaR_GWrgU9rA7NVxB9lX72pSui9nhmh0SYvsXb2jQOQ696VmkmVLn-D_QLHweNtw" style="color: #1a1a1a; text-decoration: underline;">
            DSTLD
           </a>
           became the first customer-funded fashion brand when it raised $1.7 million from customers via crowdfunding in 2016, and gave away equity to shoppers who shared the brand. They tripled sales that year.
          </p>
         </li>
         <li style="margin: 3.75px 0 3.75px 7.5px; mso-special-format: bullet;">
          <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0;">
           In 2016,
           <a href="https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFUMtuxCAM_JrlthGQkMeBQy_9jYiHm9AlEIFplb-vd_dQybLlGVujGWcQtlwufeaKrFUoa_BajHLu1bAwrwcvZjWzUNevAnCYEDWWBuxsNgZnMOT0-uBcKrZrsF9mkYO3o1Gqt2C8W2BWvJ9mL5wa2FNnNc0HSA40_EC5cgIW9Y541lv_cZOfVAeBV-dS6lw-aJdcjDS4pCYWaghuTznm7XpeA-C9WSh3uj4BA-Zy_24pE8eClpzehVhEr3o-daIzNU4gmzzT4zbwY5NdbbaicY-nHCs6ZbS5hLQR_djNAfFFkOmV5tFSwGuFZGwE_84D3wm-7OF1gk7wWyMgQnmDz5DmaRzVoBip-UxZpn-hP1dVhY4" style="color: #1a1a1a; text-decoration: underline;">
            Juno
           </a>
           tried to take on Uber by offering its drivers equity in the business. The next year, it sold to Gett, which
           <a href="https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFUEuO7CAMPE2zSwQk5LNgMZt3jcgEJ800gQjMG-X2Q7oXI1ny3-WqFQj3mC59xkysZEyLs1oMcupUPzOreysmNTGXly0hHuC8plSQncV4twK5GN4bnEvFnlrBZIZtFptRhsNozATz0M12GJCvAJzdOAsU6zCsqPE_pisGZF4_ic786L4e8l-1A_ITjMd2jUdNIZFbPdbou4TY7EjUYLBNchabOplc2Bs4z8ZfG9Up5rTkkgshZtGpjo-taCH7EWWRZ3g9en7sss3FZIL1dYOwpEMkE-9Ltf16woH-3ahMl-qPEhxdC4b7LfsRgT6yvTnRdaIO-JN9fQ7Tp3grM43DoHrFKpqNVcDwB_QLbVaD0A" style="color: #1a1a1a; text-decoration: underline;">
            shut it down in 2019
           </a>
           .
          </p>
         </li>
         <li style="margin: 3.75px 0 3.75px 7.5px; mso-special-format: bullet;">
          <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0;">
           In 2018 and 2019, several of the biggest tech companies, including Uber and Airbnb, filed letters to the SEC, asking it to allow them to share ownership with their users.
          </p>
         </li>
         <li style="margin: 3.75px 0 3.75px 7.5px; mso-special-format: bullet;">
          <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0;">
           Just this past week, Packy got an email from Airbnb letting him know that, as Host, he was eligible to buy from an allocation of IPO shares. Those shares have typically been reserved for banks and their clients.
          </p>
         </li>
        </ul>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         Those attempts have been clunky and largely unsuccessful because platforms have used old tools to solve new problems.
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         The Internet is a new way to interact, so it\xe2\x80\x99s only natural that 40 years after its invention, we will come up with digitally native ways to distribute and exchange value, unconstrained by legacy financial infrastructure.
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         Just as the first online ads looked a lot like print ads and have since evolved into digitally-native formats, we should expect digitally-native ways to distribute and exchange value on the Internet.
        </p>
        <div class="captioned-image-container-static" style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; text-align: center;">
         <figure style="display: inline-block; margin: 0 auto; width: 100%;">
          <table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" class="image-wrapper" style="margin: 1.6em auto; mso-padding-alt: 1em 0 1.6em;" width="100%">
           <tbody>
            <tr>
             <td style="text-align: center;">
             </td>
